I’ve been thinking a lot about the de-influencing trend, and how I navigate being a fashion girlie on this app in a genuine way! I love introducing y’all to brands I love and believe in, and helping folks find pieces they truly feel themselves and at home in. 

But one thing I need y’all to know point blank is that I do NOT believe a great closet is one that is bursting at the seams. Since I was a little girl, I’ve LOVED shopping, and the high that comes from buying something new and shiny. As I’ve gotten older, however, I’ve been trying to practice something that shouldn’t be that revolutionary, but kind of is: wearing what’s already in my closet. 

A big caveat to this for me is that I’m graciously gifted a fair amount of pieces, but besides that, I really have been trying to edit over add. 

I was really struck the other day by something a friend of mine said: “The most sustainable fashion is what’s already in your closet.” So while I’ll still be sharing my favorite brands and the pieces I love with y’all, I want y’all to remember that wearing and rewearing and wearing again is the most sustainable fashion there is! I need this reminder all the time, so I thought I’d share it with y’all in case you needed it today. 💖💖💖

If you don’t already know about them, allow me the honor of filling you in. Free Label is a community and ethics-based Slow Fashion brand that’s extremely size inclusive, carrying 5X-XS. They make small batch collections made in Canada with intention, and with every body in mind. 

I resonate with so much of Free Label’s vision, but especially their emphasis on encouraging folks to buy what they’re actually gonna wear, and then wearing the heck out of that item! I love that nearly all of their pieces can be worn in a variety of ways, because if there’s one thing I love: it’s OPTIONS, honey. Both of these pieces are reversible which I think is pretty dang rad. They select the comfiest textiles and silhouettes that make you feel both put together and comfy, and frankly, what more can you ask for?

I’ve seen a lot of folks posting their recaps of everything they read in 2023, and I just wanted to say this in case you haven’t heard it lately: it’s okay to go at your own pace.
